International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1] Parana
Date: Wed 15 Apr 2009
Source: Bem Parana [in Portuguese, trans. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=104313&t=suspeita-de-febre-amarela-fecha-parque-em-maringa>


8 monkeys died of suspected yellow fever in the past 15 days
------------------------------------------------------------
On Wednesday afternoon (15 [Apr 2009]), the Maringa municipality
decided to indefinitely close the Inga Park to the public. The park
closure is due to the death of 8 primates with suspected yellow fever
[virus infection] in the last 15 days.

The decision to ban access to the reserve came from the municipal
Secretariats of Environment and of Health as a precautionary measure,
at least until the investigation confirmed whether or not the deaths
were caused by yellow fever.

The Superintendent of Health Surveillance of the State Secretariat of
Health, Jose Lucio dos Santos, who was in Maringa this Thursday [9
Apr 2009], said that, pending determination of the cause of death of
the monkeys, the park should remain closed. According to him,
however, there is no reason for alarm. The forest reserve, located in
Center, has about 150 marmosets -- which live free in the forest --
and 7 monkeys which are kept in captivity.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

A map of Brazil showing the location of Parana state can be accessed at
